Beanstalk is a small language by design. Every feature has to earn its place.

### How Beanstalk decides

The language prefers one clear mechanism over many specialised syntax forms.
When a problem can be solved with an existing feature, the language doesn't
add a second way to do it.

[codeblock, $code("bst"):
    -- Templates handle text composition
    greeting = [: Hello, [name]]

    -- Choices handle runtime heterogeneity
    Status :: Ready, Waiting | reason String |;

    -- Error! handles expected failures
    result = parse(text)!
]

### What this means for you

- fewer syntax forms to learn
- code from different authors looks similar
- the compiler can give clear error messages
- optimisations happen behind the scenes
